        [
            'thread_id' => 4,
            'author_id' => 8,
            'body'      => "Weekend project: a terminal RSS reader written in plain C with zero external dependencies. It fetches feeds, parses the XML by hand, and renders everything in a tidy paged view. I wanted something that started instantly, never phoned home, and would still build cleanly in ten years.\n\nThe whole thing is under 800 lines and compiles in well under a second. No package manager, no lockfile, no node_modules black hole — just a single translation unit and the system libc. There is something deeply calming about that.\n\nLet me walk through how it came together, because a few of the decisions surprised me.\n\nThe fetcher was the easy part. I open a raw socket, write a minimal HTTP/1.1 request by hand, and read the response into a growable buffer. No TLS yet — for now I lean on a tiny local proxy for HTTPS feeds, which I admit is a cop-out. Proper TLS without a dependency is the one thing that might force my hand toward linking OpenSSL.\n\nParsing the XML by hand is where it got interesting. I did NOT want a full DOM. Feeds are messy in practice: half-closed tags, stray ampersands, CDATA sections wrapping HTML, three different date formats in the same file. So instead of a strict parser I wrote a forgiving tokenizer that walks the byte stream once, emits start/end/text events, and shrugs at anything it does not recognize. It is closer to how a browser treats tag soup than how a validator would.\n\nThe trickiest bug took me an entire evening. Some feeds embed entry bodies as escaped HTML inside the description element, so you have to unescape once to get markup, then strip that markup to get text — but a few feeds escape TWICE, and a couple do not escape at all. Detecting which case you are in without a heuristic that breaks the others was genuinely fiddly. I settled on unescaping until the result stops changing, capped at two passes, which is hacky but has not failed me yet.\n\nRendering is a paged view, like less. I measure the terminal with ioctl, lay out entries into pages, and let you scroll with j/k and jump between feeds with tab. Reflowing on resize was a nice touch that took ten minutes and made it feel real.\n\nMemory management is arena-based. Each refresh allocates into a single arena and frees the whole thing at once when the next refresh starts. No per-node frees, no use-after-free, no leak chasing. For a program with a clear request/response lifecycle this pattern is a joy and I will reach for it again.\n\nThings I am still unsure about: the date parsing is held together with hope, the config format is just key=value lines I parse myself, and there is no caching layer so it refetches everything on every refresh. None of that matters at my scale but it would all bite under real use.\n\nScreenshots and the repo link are below. Feedback very welcome — especially on the parser and on how you would tackle TLS without pulling in a giant dependency. I would love to keep the zero-dependency promise but I am not sure it survives contact with the modern web.\n\nThanks for reading this far. If you build something similar I would genuinely love to compare notes.",
